WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:12.074
Support us and become VIP member 
to remove all ads from www.OpenSubtitles.org

2
00:00:29.541 --> 00:00:32.333
Daddy. Sherlock won't play with me.

3
00:00:34.041 --> 00:00:35.750
Get up. you idiot.

4
00:00:36.500 --> 00:00:37.726
Play with her.

5
00:00:37.750 --> 00:00:40.226
Bea? Bea!

6
00:00:40.250 --> 00:00:41.601
Where is she?

7
00:00:41.625 --> 00:00:43.226
Cordelia? Beatrice!

8
00:00:43.250 --> 00:00:45.267
- Beatrice!
- Help your mother!

9
00:00:45.291 --> 00:00:46.351
Find her!

10
00:01:04.875 --> 00:01:05.958
Find her!

11
00:01:30.625 --> 00:01:32.226
I don't know why you're
getting so agitated.

12
00:01:32.250 --> 00:01:34.142
I just said you have a
rather large cranium.

13
00:01:37.375 --> 00:01:38.375
Mr Holmes.

14
00:01:40.208 --> 00:01:42.601
You'll have to be
quicker than that. Barney.

15
00:01:42.625 --> 00:01:45.517
Saw that one coming a mile off.

16
00:01:46.458 --> 00:01:48.458
You need to hide your
intent more. Barney.

17
00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:04.559
Break it up. Break it up!

18
00:02:04.583 --> 00:02:07.767
Is that you. brother dear?

19
00:02:07.791 --> 00:02:08.976
'Tis. brother dear.

20
00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:11.500
Put him down. Barney. Easy.

21
00:02:15.916 --> 00:02:17.309
Nice of you to pop by.

22
00:02:17.333 --> 00:02:19.791
Holiday is over. Follow me. Sherlock.

23
00:02:23.750 --> 00:02:26.000
Really. I meant no offence. Barney.

24
00:02:27.416 --> 00:02:28.934
Captain. Bob. Mr Dickie.

25
00:02:28.958 --> 00:02:31.101
Sherlock. your brother
couldn't get us out. could he?

26
00:02:31.125 --> 00:02:32.559
Mycroft. you heard the question.

27
00:02:32.583 --> 00:02:35.166
I have one card to play.
Sherlock. It's either you or him.

28
00:02:37.083 --> 00:02:38.833
Two years will fly by. mr Dickie.

29
00:02:39.791 --> 00:02:41.833
What exactly landed
you in prison this time?

30
00:02:42.916 --> 00:02:43.976
Reading.

31
00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:46.934
Reading doesn't get you
arrested. So. what did?

32
00:02:46.958 --> 00:02:49.267
Oliver twist.

33
00:02:49.291 --> 00:02:51.309
I rather took a shine to the artful dodger.

34
00:02:51.333 --> 00:02:52.851
I'm so sorry. sir.

35
00:02:52.875 --> 00:02:54.059
A pickpocket by trade.

36
00:02:54.083 --> 00:02:56.309
I thought to myself. "I
wonder if I could do that?"

37
00:02:56.333 --> 00:02:57.583
Allow me. sir.

38
00:02:59.125 --> 00:03:00.517
This fell out of your pocket.

39
00:03:00.541 --> 00:03:02.684
The problem is. extracting
a gentlemen's wallet

40
00:03:02.708 --> 00:03:04.434
isn't as challenging as returning it.

41
00:03:04.458 --> 00:03:05.601
- Thief!
- No. no.

42
00:03:06.791 --> 00:03:09.476
Why would you be returning
the wallet with its contents intact?

43
00:03:09.500 --> 00:03:11.559
It's the extraction that is the attraction.

44
00:03:12.500 --> 00:03:15.267
That explains the first three months
but you were sent down for six.

45
00:03:15.291 --> 00:03:18.601
I am considering
transportation to Australia.

46
00:03:18.625 --> 00:03:20.476
I'm afraid that won't be
possible. your honour.

47
00:03:20.500 --> 00:03:22.517
Excuse me?

48
00:03:22.541 --> 00:03:24.684
1857. The penal servitude act.

49
00:03:24.708 --> 00:03:25.976
According to precedent.

50
00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:28.392
a court is either bound by the
decisions of the court above it

51
00:03:28.416 --> 00:03:30.517
or the decisions of a
court of equivalent standing

52
00:03:30.541 --> 00:03:33.267
thus. in this case making
it conspicuously impossible

53
00:03:33.291 --> 00:03:35.976
to send a man to Australia...
two months for contempt.

54
00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:37.726
As you could be in breach of the act.

55
00:03:37.750 --> 00:03:39.476
- Three months.
- And in an ironic turn of fate.

56
00:03:39.500 --> 00:03:42.142
could subsequently find
yourself stood in this very dock.

57
00:03:42.166 --> 00:03:43.809
Six months!

58
00:03:43.833 --> 00:03:47.184
I find it astonishing that the
judge didn't see your point of view.

59
00:03:47.208 --> 00:03:48.875
My point exactly.

60
00:03:50.166 --> 00:03:51.833
You could have got me out sooner.

61
00:04:59.041 --> 00:05:03.351
There it is. I knew there was a
face underneath that nest of crows.

62
00:05:03.375 --> 00:05:05.892
So. how was the food?

63
00:05:05.916 --> 00:05:09.184
The chef was often a little
heavy with the weevils in the gruel

64
00:05:09.208 --> 00:05:13.017
but the claret was excellent.
You should try it sometime.

65
00:05:13.041 --> 00:05:16.767
Guess I'm quite happy where I am.
Respectable job in the civil service.

66
00:05:16.791 --> 00:05:18.976
Respectable or conventional?

67
00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:20.183
- Secure.
- Predictable?

68
00:05:20.207 --> 00:05:21.558
- Influential.
- Tedious.

69
00:05:21.582 --> 00:05:25.558
Reliable. consistent.
stable and responsible.

70
00:05:25.582 --> 00:05:27.308
You should try it sometime.

71
00:05:27.332 --> 00:05:31.541
And on that note. prepare
yourself. I come bearing a gift.

72
00:05:32.125 --> 00:05:33.183
Apprehensive.

73
00:05:33.207 --> 00:05:35.308
I've secured you a place at Oxford.

74
00:05:35.332 --> 00:05:37.726
Arguably the greatest
university in the world.

75
00:05:37.750 --> 00:05:40.308
- You have. brother dear?
- I have. brother dear.

76
00:05:40.332 --> 00:05:42.767
Well. I'm surprised. Grateful.

77
00:05:42.791 --> 00:05:43.791
Aw.

78
00:05:44.791 --> 00:05:46.433
I've always been rather fascinated

79
00:05:46.457 --> 00:05:48.476
by a life dedicated to
the pursuit of learning.

80
00:05:48.500 --> 00:05:52.101
And I'll be there on government business.
So. I'll be able to keep an eye on you.

81
00:05:52.125 --> 00:05:55.017
Make sure your hair is brushed.
your teeth are clean. shoes are shiny.

82
00:05:55.041 --> 00:05:56.433
- When do we go?
- Imminently.

83
00:05:56.457 --> 00:05:58.517
I'm touched. Moved.

84
00:05:58.541 --> 00:05:59.582
Get dressed.

85
00:06:00.208 --> 00:06:01.958
We're going to pay
our respects to mummy.

86
00:06:10.541 --> 00:06:14.041
Mr Holmes. We've moved
your mother to a bigger room.

87
00:06:27.125 --> 00:06:28.183
Sherlock.

88
00:06:28.207 --> 00:06:30.101
Hello. mother. Please don't stand.

89
00:06:30.125 --> 00:06:31.541
My darling.

90
00:06:32.666 --> 00:06:35.332
Were the three months
hard. my darling?

91
00:06:35.832 --> 00:06:37.767
It was quite an education. really.

92
00:06:37.791 --> 00:06:39.642
Oof. Does that hurt?

93
00:06:39.666 --> 00:06:42.541
Only when I laugh.

94
00:06:43.291 --> 00:06:46.875
Father wrote to me. He's
in Vienna. Sounds well.

95
00:06:50.082 --> 00:06:51.541
They're listening to me.

96
00:06:54.582 --> 00:06:55.582
A whirring.

97
00:06:56.875 --> 00:06:58.457
All the time.

98
00:06:59.875 --> 00:07:02.184
They can hear everything I say.

99
00:07:02.208 --> 00:07:04.916
And there's a man with a bird claw.

100
00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:07.583
And he's coming back for me.

101
00:07:11.333 --> 00:07:14.333
I'm sorry I haven't been able
to visit much recently. mother.

102
00:07:14.833 --> 00:07:16.142
It's not your fault.

103
00:07:16.166 --> 00:07:19.582
But I'm in Oxford now. I'll be close by.

104
00:07:20.707 --> 00:07:22.125
And I can visit much more often.

105
00:07:24.457 --> 00:07:26.041
You have to promise me something.

106
00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:28.058
Anything.

107
00:07:28.082 --> 00:07:30.832
You must stay out of trouble.

108
00:07:31.457 --> 00:07:35.207
Understood. I will. No more trouble.

109
00:07:35.791 --> 00:07:37.041
I won't lose you too.

110
00:07:46.666 --> 00:07:51.183
University college was founded in 1249.
making it the oldest college in Oxford.

111
00:07:51.207 --> 00:07:52.976
I did try to get you into there.

112
00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:57.582
I tried balliol college too.
in 1263. And merton. 1264.

113
00:07:58.166 --> 00:08:02.017
Sadly. none of the founding
colleges would take you. So...

114
00:08:02.041 --> 00:08:05.500
I suppose I'll have to put up with
the clumsy modernity of 1458 then?

115
00:08:07.875 --> 00:08:10.142
Now. I got your foot in the door.

116
00:08:10.166 --> 00:08:12.625
Time to start taking
advantage of your advantage.

117
00:08:15.958 --> 00:08:17.976
There's something you're
not telling me. isn't there?

118
00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:20.332
You'll thank me for it. One day.

119
00:08:21.416 --> 00:08:22.726
Smudger.

120
00:08:22.750 --> 00:08:23.750
Mr Holmes.

121
00:08:24.541 --> 00:08:25.601
Sherlock Holmes?

122
00:08:25.625 --> 00:08:26.625
That'll be me. sir.

123
00:08:27.750 --> 00:08:29.207
This is yours. sir.

124
00:08:31.291 --> 00:08:32.291
Come on.

125
00:08:33.665 --> 00:08:36.016
- Mycroft.
- Yes?

126
00:08:36.040 --> 00:08:38.266
Why is the head Porter
proffering an apron?

127
00:08:38.290 --> 00:08:41.040
You're a smart boy. Work it out.

128
00:08:41.832 --> 00:08:43.750
I'm to be a Porter. not a student?

129
00:08:44.250 --> 00:08:47.059
No. You've got to work
your way up to be a Porter.

130
00:08:47.083 --> 00:08:49.391
- You're a scout.
- I'm a scout?

131
00:08:49.415 --> 00:08:51.708
- And a scout does?
- Whatever I tell him to do.

132
00:08:54.290 --> 00:08:56.351
I'm here to serve and not to learn?

133
00:08:56.375 --> 00:08:58.641
No. no. You'll learn. all right.

134
00:08:58.665 --> 00:09:01.875
Come along. son. The shitters aren't
gonna clean themselves. are they?

135
00:09:03.125 --> 00:09:04.125
Mycroft?

136
00:09:04.666 --> 00:09:06.000
Bon appétit?

137
00:09:07.041 --> 00:09:08.208
Mycroft.

138
00:09:12.458 --> 00:09:13.833
The shitters. sir?

139
00:09:22.916 --> 00:09:24.250
Hyah!

140
00:09:25.583 --> 00:09:29.226
Mr chen and I appreciate
your government sending you

141
00:09:29.250 --> 00:09:33.309
to escort us from London to
Oxford. but it wasn't necessary.

142
00:09:33.333 --> 00:09:36.708
Princess. I can assure
you the honour is all mine.

143
00:09:37.750 --> 00:09:41.625
My government values our
relationship with China very highly.

144
00:09:42.208 --> 00:09:44.583
We wouldn't want anything to go wrong.

145
00:09:45.290 --> 00:09:48.415
Is that why you've
arranged an armed escort?

146
00:09:49.290 --> 00:09:50.290
Hyah!

147
00:10:03.125 --> 00:10:04.750
Hyah! Hyah!

148
00:10:07.041 --> 00:10:08.791
Whoa! Whoa!

149
00:10:15.416 --> 00:10:17.041
Are we all having a lovely day?

150
00:10:17.750 --> 00:10:20.684
I said. "are we all having a lovely day?"

151
00:10:20.708 --> 00:10:22.017
Yes. yes.

152
00:10:22.041 --> 00:10:23.083
Good.

153
00:10:24.875 --> 00:10:26.333
I won't hold you up for long.

154
00:10:27.291 --> 00:10:28.916
I'm just here for the scrolls.

155
00:10:40.583 --> 00:10:41.583
Thank you. darling.

156
00:10:42.708 --> 00:10:43.708
What about her?

157
00:10:46.125 --> 00:10:48.601
What about her? Our
job is to take the scrolls.

158
00:10:48.625 --> 00:10:50.790
She's a Princess. Think of the ransom.

159
00:10:58.583 --> 00:11:00.642
- You're coming with us. Princess.
- No!

160
00:11:01.958 --> 00:11:03.000
Let's go.

161
00:12:17.500 --> 00:12:18.750
Princess?

162
00:12:29.750 --> 00:12:31.083
More tea. scout!

163
00:12:32.040 --> 00:12:33.833
Right away. professor.

164
00:12:53.165 --> 00:12:55.266
What are you doing with those?

165
00:12:55.290 --> 00:12:58.476
Tidying. sir. I do apologise.
professor Thompson.

166
00:12:58.500 --> 00:13:03.500
No good ever comes poking your nose
into business that does not concern you.

167
00:13:04.125 --> 00:13:05.125
I apologise. sir.

168
00:13:07.083 --> 00:13:09.267
- Did you write this?
- Yes. I did.

169
00:13:09.291 --> 00:13:12.726
Recently published. Rather
well received. if I may say so.

170
00:13:12.750 --> 00:13:15.250
- May I?
- Yes. of course.

171
00:13:19.416 --> 00:13:22.101
A scout interested in mathematics?

172
00:13:22.125 --> 00:13:26.559
My father always instilled in me the
love for reading. Taught me to be curious.

173
00:13:26.583 --> 00:13:28.059
Curiosity.

174
00:13:28.083 --> 00:13:29.541
The greatest virtue.

175
00:13:30.041 --> 00:13:31.476
But not if you're a cat.

176
00:13:33.125 --> 00:13:35.000
Would you mind if I borrowed this?

177
00:13:35.625 --> 00:13:39.516
Not at all… Sherlock Holmes. sir.

178
00:13:39.540 --> 00:13:42.125
Sherlock? It's an unusual name.

179
00:14:01.291 --> 00:14:03.351
This is for the Chinese Princess.

180
00:14:03.375 --> 00:14:04.559
Just arrived.

181
00:14:04.583 --> 00:14:06.333
Old court. room 2b.

182
00:14:07.958 --> 00:14:09.916
At your service. mr smudger.

183
00:14:10.916 --> 00:14:12.041
Good lad.

184
00:14:27.333 --> 00:14:28.916
Scout.

185
00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:36.000
Your luggage. ma'am.

186
00:14:36.540 --> 00:14:38.083
Please. place it on the desk.

187
00:14:40.458 --> 00:14:42.500
You want me to clear it?

188
00:14:44.750 --> 00:14:46.208
I can do it myself.

189
00:14:47.540 --> 00:14:51.333
How does a college Porter end up
speaking mandarin from the gansu province?

190
00:14:52.750 --> 00:14:57.125
I worked in whitechapel for a shoemaker.

191
00:14:57.583 --> 00:14:58.915
He was from dunhuang.

192
00:14:59.875 --> 00:15:01.250
Your pronunciation…

193
00:15:01.791 --> 00:15:03.208
…is terrible.

194
00:15:03.750 --> 00:15:05.101
But just about intelligible.

195
00:15:05.125 --> 00:15:07.267
The shoemaker had a dependency.

196
00:15:07.291 --> 00:15:10.351
- Do you mean he was a drunk?
- That was his poison of choice. yes.

197
00:15:10.375 --> 00:15:12.291
Which explained your slurred delivery.

198
00:15:15.958 --> 00:15:16.958
Your highness.

199
00:15:18.958 --> 00:15:21.375
Pray. silence for sir bucephalus hodge.

200
00:15:23.500 --> 00:15:28.767
While visiting my. not
inconsiderable business interests

201
00:15:28.791 --> 00:15:30.833
in this glorious empire of ours.

202
00:15:31.666 --> 00:15:36.583
it struck me that it was time to give back.

203
00:15:37.165 --> 00:15:40.809
So. it is. with great delight
that I announce this term

204
00:15:40.833 --> 00:15:43.476
the opening of my new science building.

205
00:15:43.500 --> 00:15:47.125
A brilliant addition to
this glittering university.

206
00:15:48.415 --> 00:15:51.016
Now. scholars. On your feet.

207
00:15:55.165 --> 00:15:58.934
I present to you my hodge scholars.

208
00:16:02.166 --> 00:16:03.601
Take a good look.

209
00:16:03.625 --> 00:16:07.625
These students will be
generals. prime ministers.

210
00:16:08.500 --> 00:16:12.434
leaders who will guide our
world into the 20th century.

211
00:16:12.458 --> 00:16:16.642
Enjoy learning. Enjoy
your youth. Welcome!

212
00:16:21.333 --> 00:16:23.434
I came up in '23.

213
00:16:23.458 --> 00:16:26.184
Itchy feet. though. Didn't stay long.

214
00:16:26.208 --> 00:16:29.392
And may I say. sir. no one
has had a greater impact

215
00:16:29.416 --> 00:16:31.267
on expanding the
British empire than you.

216
00:16:31.291 --> 00:16:33.641
Everything to your satisfaction. sirs?

217
00:16:33.665 --> 00:16:35.309
Yes. thank you. Thank you.

218
00:16:37.290 --> 00:16:39.309
- You quite sure?
- Yes. fine. Thank you.

219
00:16:39.333 --> 00:16:41.934
Nothing else I can get you? I
am. of course. at your service.

220
00:16:41.958 --> 00:16:43.934
At your Beck and call.
as you well know. sir.

221
00:16:43.958 --> 00:16:45.351
I said I'm fine. thank you.

222
00:16:45.375 --> 00:16:47.976
- You know this young man?
- Yes he does. sir. Very well. sir.

223
00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:50.351
- How so?
- I'm his lowly brother. sir.

224
00:16:50.375 --> 00:16:53.016
What? Brother? No.

225
00:16:53.040 --> 00:16:54.184
Is this true. mycroft?

226
00:16:54.208 --> 00:16:56.351
It's not a very interesting story. sir.

227
00:16:56.375 --> 00:16:57.540
But is it true?

228
00:16:59.500 --> 00:17:01.892
Yes. indeed. he is my brother.

229
00:17:01.916 --> 00:17:04.559
- So how did he end up serving here?
- Redemption. sir.

230
00:17:04.583 --> 00:17:05.684
From what?

231
00:17:05.708 --> 00:17:08.559
Prison. Her majesty's pleasure.

232
00:17:08.583 --> 00:17:11.266
How could you say this
wasn't interesting. mycroft?

233
00:17:11.290 --> 00:17:12.434
Do carry on. young man.

234
00:17:12.458 --> 00:17:15.766
Well. my magnanimous brother here

235
00:17:15.790 --> 00:17:17.516
took pity on the black
sheep of the family.

236
00:17:17.540 --> 00:17:19.601
for which I am eternally grateful.

237
00:17:19.625 --> 00:17:20.976
More wine. your lordship?

238
00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:24.351
So. tell me… …you
have the same parents?

239
00:17:24.375 --> 00:17:25.375
Yes we do. sir.

240
00:17:25.915 --> 00:17:29.559
Although. sadly. we only really get
to see each other at. family funerals.

241
00:17:29.583 --> 00:17:30.875
court hearings. the like.

242
00:17:32.333 --> 00:17:34.559
- Sir. today…
- that's quite enough.

243
00:17:34.583 --> 00:17:36.375
…Is your special day.

244
00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:39.892
Your scholars are an inspiration to us all.

245
00:17:39.916 --> 00:17:43.601
So. tell me. young man…
…what was your crime?

246
00:17:43.625 --> 00:17:46.833
Larceny. Thieving. Theft. Petty theft.

247
00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:50.767
Although those days are
well and truly behind me.

248
00:17:50.791 --> 00:17:54.017
spiritually and permanently.

249
00:17:54.041 --> 00:17:55.851
There we are. Reformed.

250
00:17:55.875 --> 00:17:59.375
Was a taker. now a
giver. Reborn to serve. sir.

251
00:17:59.875 --> 00:18:03.434
Thank you. I'm sure we can take care of
ourselves from now on. brother dearest.

252
00:18:03.458 --> 00:18:04.458
Very well. sirs.

253
00:18:07.041 --> 00:18:08.476
I'm so sorry. sir.

254
00:18:08.500 --> 00:18:10.559
No need to apologise. mycroft.

255
00:18:10.583 --> 00:18:12.666
Your brother's the most
interesting thing about you.

256
00:18:16.125 --> 00:18:19.434
One should assume here
that x is greater than y.

257
00:18:19.458 --> 00:18:21.809
and define the powers of x and y

258
00:18:21.833 --> 00:18:24.892
using a holomorphic branch of log.

259
00:18:24.916 --> 00:18:30.000
defined on an open disk
of radius centred at x.

260
00:18:33.375 --> 00:18:34.684
Y.

261
00:18:36.500 --> 00:18:39.458
Why? Why. because
that is how it works.

262
00:18:41.416 --> 00:18:46.416
An open disk of radius centred at
y. not x. professor Thompson. sir.

263
00:18:49.958 --> 00:18:51.333
My apologies.

264
00:18:52.208 --> 00:18:53.208
Y.

265
00:18:53.916 --> 00:18:56.541
Who so generously
thought to correct me?

266
00:18:59.916 --> 00:19:04.916
Mr Holmes the scout. I
see you've read my book.

267
00:19:05.500 --> 00:19:07.184
I did. professor Thompson.

268
00:19:07.208 --> 00:19:11.267
Which is more than I can
say for some of my students.

269
00:19:13.375 --> 00:19:15.291
Saved by the bell.

270
00:19:15.916 --> 00:19:16.976
Homework.

271
00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:21.375
Find me all the solutions of this quintic.

272
00:19:43.833 --> 00:19:45.833
You're having trouble
finding the solutions?

273
00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:49.291
Don't worry about that.

274
00:19:50.750 --> 00:19:54.208
You just have to get
yourself some new numbers.

275
00:19:54.791 --> 00:19:58.833
These solutions. they're
not real. They're imaginary.

276
00:20:01.083 --> 00:20:04.458
That means even if you can't see
the target. you can still shoot for it.

277
00:20:05.833 --> 00:20:07.476
So you're a mathematician now.

278
00:20:07.500 --> 00:20:12.434
A Porter. a waiter. a candlestick
maker. and a kleptomaniac.

279
00:20:12.458 --> 00:20:16.392
Was a taker. now a giver.

280
00:20:16.416 --> 00:20:18.517
Does hodge's pocket
watch keep good time?

281
00:20:18.541 --> 00:20:22.184
They say that it's the unconscious
desire of every thief to be caught.

282
00:20:22.208 --> 00:20:25.267
That it's the fear of incarceration
that gives freedom its currency.

283
00:20:25.291 --> 00:20:29.267
The fundamental fault of man is to
think the enemy is external. not internal.

284
00:20:29.291 --> 00:20:30.934
Prison is in here. not out there.

285
00:20:33.500 --> 00:20:36.250
Look at you with your art of war.

286
00:20:40.708 --> 00:20:41.750
James moriarty.

287
00:20:45.833 --> 00:20:46.833
Sherlock Holmes.

288
00:20:51.958 --> 00:20:53.208
It's a long line.

289
00:20:53.791 --> 00:20:55.809
And I'm not a great one for waiting.

290
00:20:55.833 --> 00:20:57.125
Waiting for what?

291
00:20:57.708 --> 00:20:59.041
We're going to a party.

292
00:21:00.041 --> 00:21:02.142
We're not quite dressed for
this. Are you even invited?

293
00:21:02.166 --> 00:21:04.434
I don't think you need
to worry about that.

294
00:21:04.458 --> 00:21:06.226
You just follow my lead.

295
00:21:06.250 --> 00:21:09.875
Good evening. ladies and gentlemen.
May I see your invitations. please?

296
00:21:11.500 --> 00:21:14.101
Sirs. madams. please
stand tight to the wall

297
00:21:14.125 --> 00:21:16.476
to keep the path clear
for the other students.

298
00:21:16.500 --> 00:21:18.684
This is marvellous. I won't be a moment.

299
00:21:18.708 --> 00:21:19.958
Wonderful dress. madam.

300
00:21:24.333 --> 00:21:26.208
Excuse me. Excuse me.

301
00:21:27.791 --> 00:21:29.434
Leave this with me.

302
00:21:29.458 --> 00:21:33.791
Sir. You have a dramatic
split in the back of your jacket.

303
00:21:40.291 --> 00:21:42.934
Two sazeracs. There you go.

304
00:21:42.958 --> 00:21:44.625
- Thank you.
- My pleasure.

305
00:21:47.041 --> 00:21:49.309
Excuse me. sir. You cannot take that.

306
00:21:49.333 --> 00:21:50.976
You're absolutely right. sir.

307
00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:54.291
But I can borrow it. and I shall
return it to its cradle UN moment.

308
00:21:56.708 --> 00:22:00.041
Now. look to this day. for it is life.

309
00:22:06.833 --> 00:22:08.601
- You're the scout.
- Indeed.

310
00:22:08.625 --> 00:22:10.809
- How did you get in here?
- I invited him.

311
00:22:10.833 --> 00:22:11.892
And who invited you?

312
00:22:11.916 --> 00:22:14.541
No one. And yet. here I am.

313
00:22:15.458 --> 00:22:17.500
If I wish to socialise with a cleaner.

314
00:22:18.166 --> 00:22:20.666
I'd have a party in the servants' quarters.

315
00:22:21.333 --> 00:22:24.517
So if you wouldn't mind.
I'd ask you to leave.

316
00:22:24.541 --> 00:22:27.142
He might be a cleaner. but
he's a very clever cleaner.

317
00:22:27.166 --> 00:22:30.916
Such fun. At last we have characters
at one of your parties. peregrine.

318
00:22:31.666 --> 00:22:32.708
I have an idea.

319
00:22:33.958 --> 00:22:38.059
You outsmart the scout. and
he'll leave without further protest.

320
00:22:38.083 --> 00:22:42.101
You take a good. long look at him.
and you tell us what you can glean.

321
00:22:42.125 --> 00:22:45.684
- And then he'll do the same to you.
- And then I'll be the judge of who wins.

322
00:22:45.708 --> 00:22:47.166
Very well.

323
00:22:48.250 --> 00:22:49.375
Show me your hand.

324
00:22:51.041 --> 00:22:52.601
Interesting signet ring.

325
00:22:52.625 --> 00:22:55.083
I notice an absence of any type of ring.

326
00:22:55.791 --> 00:22:57.184
And no callouses.

327
00:22:57.208 --> 00:23:01.309
He's clearly not intimately acquainted
with anything approaching hard labour.

328
00:23:01.333 --> 00:23:04.208
So not just a servant. a lazy one too.

329
00:23:04.708 --> 00:23:08.291
Had you not considered that
he wears gloves? So what else?

330
00:23:10.625 --> 00:23:13.809
That's it? Well. you
had a promising start.

331
00:23:13.833 --> 00:23:15.267
but you'd no follow through.

332
00:23:15.291 --> 00:23:17.708
What you made was an
observation. not a deduction.

333
00:23:18.541 --> 00:23:21.541
No callouses. so how does
he find himself in this position?

334
00:23:22.708 --> 00:23:25.559
Well. I'd say he got into a
spot of bother along the way.

335
00:23:25.583 --> 00:23:28.601
He got kicked out of school. so
he brought shame upon his parents.

336
00:23:28.625 --> 00:23:32.059
and then his father made him take
this position to teach him a lesson.

337
00:23:32.083 --> 00:23:33.708
- Not quite.
- Brother.

338
00:23:35.500 --> 00:23:37.000
A high achiever. Am I correct?

339
00:23:37.541 --> 00:23:38.541
Spot on.

340
00:23:39.041 --> 00:23:41.351
Wasn't so hard. was it?

341
00:23:41.375 --> 00:23:42.375
My turn.

342
00:23:44.125 --> 00:23:46.601
Your signet ring? The crest?

343
00:23:46.625 --> 00:23:48.934
Your ancestor was
the count of boulogne.

344
00:23:48.958 --> 00:23:50.392
Fought at the battle of Hastings.

345
00:23:50.416 --> 00:23:54.184
"He was 5'2" and he had a face like a
cow's udder. but he fought like a titan.

346
00:23:54.208 --> 00:23:56.892
So. ugly. yes. but
magnificent nonetheless.

347
00:23:56.916 --> 00:24:00.517
Now. as is consistent with custom. a
man knows he must wear his signet ring

348
00:24:00.541 --> 00:24:04.791
facing inward to represent content.
not outward to represent form.

349
00:24:05.541 --> 00:24:09.059
Inward for noble lion.
outward for tabby cat.

350
00:24:09.083 --> 00:24:12.041
Tell me. Which direction
does your ring point?

351
00:24:13.291 --> 00:24:17.101
Peregrine. that must hurt.

352
00:24:17.125 --> 00:24:19.208
Not as much as this is going to hurt.

353
00:24:30.833 --> 00:24:32.208
Your ladyship.

354
00:24:33.833 --> 00:24:35.833
- Until next time.
- I look forward to that.

355
00:24:36.458 --> 00:24:37.476
Whiskey.

356
00:24:37.500 --> 00:24:39.017
- Yes. of course.
- Hey!

357
00:25:03.833 --> 00:25:09.250
At least you can run 'cause
you definitely can't fight.

358
00:25:11.166 --> 00:25:16.142
Yes. well. I've always been
more of a thinker than a fighter.

359
00:25:16.166 --> 00:25:19.666
Upstairs for thinking.
downstairs for dancing.

360
00:25:20.375 --> 00:25:23.184
You might want to
re-strategize that philosophy.

361
00:25:23.208 --> 00:25:24.892
The two aren't mutually exclusive.

362
00:25:24.916 --> 00:25:27.208
Why do you think an
emperor employs a general?

363
00:25:29.583 --> 00:25:33.125
The hand of mercy means nothing
without the hand of judgement.

364
00:25:33.791 --> 00:25:35.791
Slap needs a tickle. tickle needs a slap.

365
00:25:36.500 --> 00:25:37.958
There's an art to fighting.

366
00:25:39.916 --> 00:25:41.166
There's an art to war.

367
00:25:42.333 --> 00:25:45.601
These belonged to the
father of Princess shou'an.

368
00:25:45.625 --> 00:25:46.976
The art of war.

369
00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:50.416
Part of the original
scrolls. Fifth century bc.

370
00:25:52.791 --> 00:25:56.250
"In order to know your enemy.
you must become your enemy."

371
00:25:58.333 --> 00:26:00.000
My father had a copy of this.

372
00:26:01.791 --> 00:26:03.583
Didn't do him much good. though.

373
00:26:04.583 --> 00:26:06.291
I'd say it's worth a pound or two.

374
00:26:07.500 --> 00:26:08.708
Let's steal it.

375
00:26:09.625 --> 00:26:12.875
Or better still. you're
the expert. You steal it.

376
00:26:13.541 --> 00:26:15.791
I don't think that's a very good idea.

377
00:26:17.500 --> 00:26:19.250
That's a shame.

378
00:26:20.625 --> 00:26:23.541
- You could do a lot with the money.
- Could do more with my freedom.

379
00:26:47.250 --> 00:26:48.916
Tell me it wasn't you.

380
00:26:49.625 --> 00:26:52.958
- What wasn't me. sir?
- The police are on their way.

381
00:26:53.791 --> 00:26:55.017
Not quite sure I'm following.

382
00:26:55.041 --> 00:26:58.059
The robbery last night.
The library. You had keys.

383
00:26:58.083 --> 00:27:01.875
The scrolls have been stolen. and
you was the last one seen going in.

384
00:27:03.458 --> 00:27:06.184
I hope for your sake
it wasn't you. my boy.

385
00:27:06.208 --> 00:27:07.708
Excuse me. mr smudger.

386
00:27:18.250 --> 00:27:21.767
Just for clarity's sake. we didn't
take those scrolls last night. did we?

387
00:27:21.791 --> 00:27:22.791
No. we didn't.

388
00:27:27.750 --> 00:27:30.434
Hodge thinks we did.
He was just in here.

389
00:27:30.458 --> 00:27:32.017
What did he say?

390
00:27:32.041 --> 00:27:33.125
He took my scholarship.

391
00:27:34.500 --> 00:27:35.601
Dear.

392
00:27:35.625 --> 00:27:38.041
Yeah. so without that. I can't stay here.

393
00:27:40.916 --> 00:27:41.916
Lucky you.

394
00:27:44.291 --> 00:27:45.392
Gets better.

395
00:27:45.416 --> 00:27:48.083
Go on. I can hardly wait.

396
00:27:49.458 --> 00:27:51.541
Well. you'll be going back to prison.

397
00:27:52.083 --> 00:27:53.083
Lucky me!

398
00:27:56.000 --> 00:27:57.458
I'm going to find my brother.

399
00:27:59.750 --> 00:28:01.625
Get dressed. Meet me in the library.

400
00:28:05.625 --> 00:28:06.708
Mycroft.

401
00:28:08.708 --> 00:28:12.791
Stay out of trouble. One simple request.

402
00:28:13.416 --> 00:28:15.351
Is there any point
protesting my innocence?

403
00:28:15.375 --> 00:28:16.767
Sherlock Holmes.

404
00:28:16.791 --> 00:28:20.476
What is that? You
need my help. don't you?

405
00:28:20.500 --> 00:28:22.267
- No.
- Sherlock Holmes.

406
00:28:22.291 --> 00:28:24.476
I am arresting you in suspicion of theft.

407
00:28:24.500 --> 00:28:27.684
- You won't need those.
- Sir. stop. I am a constable.

408
00:28:27.708 --> 00:28:29.291
Yes. the clue is in the uniform.

409
00:28:29.875 --> 00:28:32.351
Constable lestrade of
Oxford city police force.

410
00:28:32.375 --> 00:28:35.166
And I am mycroft Holmes of
her majesty's foreign office.

411
00:28:35.750 --> 00:28:38.226
I'm in Oxford to assist
sir bucephalus hodge

412
00:28:38.250 --> 00:28:40.226
with the opening of his
new science building.

413
00:28:40.250 --> 00:28:42.851
Surely this is more detective's work?

414
00:28:42.875 --> 00:28:46.476
I thought I'd make initial enquiries.
Early worm catches the bird.

415
00:28:46.500 --> 00:28:47.976
Could be in trouble here.

416
00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:50.101
I'm trying to prevent you
professional embarrassment

417
00:28:50.125 --> 00:28:51.892
of being reprimanded
by your chief officer.

418
00:28:51.916 --> 00:28:54.767
who happens to be my bridge
partner and is. as you know.

419
00:28:54.791 --> 00:28:57.142
a stickler for due process.

420
00:28:57.166 --> 00:28:59.833
Yes. sir. Quite.

421
00:29:02.333 --> 00:29:03.476
- Thank you. sir.
- Good man.

422
00:29:03.500 --> 00:29:05.041
Sir. Come on.

423
00:29:07.666 --> 00:29:09.500
I need you to get me into the library.

424
00:29:10.333 --> 00:29:13.375
You got ten minutes.
Don't embarrass me again.

425
00:29:13.875 --> 00:29:16.517
- You know what we're looking for?
- Not really. no.

426
00:29:16.541 --> 00:29:18.642
I thank you for keeping me updated.

427
00:29:18.666 --> 00:29:21.291
but I would like to see
the crime scene for myself.

428
00:29:23.750 --> 00:29:26.791
A hole in the window.
Wonder what that's for?

429
00:29:28.041 --> 00:29:29.101
You should be a detective.

430
00:29:29.125 --> 00:29:32.309
Hard to escape my
powers of observation.

431
00:29:32.333 --> 00:29:34.934
What are these powers of
observation telling you now?

432
00:29:34.958 --> 00:29:38.125
There has been. wait for it. a break-in.

433
00:29:39.166 --> 00:29:40.166
Astounding.

434
00:29:41.333 --> 00:29:44.059
How did you develop these
skills of penetrating deduction?

435
00:29:44.083 --> 00:29:46.351
We've been gifted a couple of paw prints.

436
00:29:46.375 --> 00:29:48.541
There's a hook there.
who's missing his guest.

437
00:29:50.000 --> 00:29:51.434
Think I've clocked the guest.

438
00:29:51.458 --> 00:29:53.041
Your ten minutes are up.

439
00:29:53.625 --> 00:29:58.101
Mycroft. would you mind telling me
why your brother. the prime suspect.

440
00:29:58.125 --> 00:29:59.892
is standing at the scene of the crime?

441
00:29:59.916 --> 00:30:02.684
I think it only fair he has a
chance to defend himself. sir.

442
00:30:02.708 --> 00:30:05.767
No. he doesn't. Not here. He has a
chance to defend himself in a court of law.

443
00:30:05.791 --> 00:30:07.833
- Constables. remove him.
- Right away. sir.

444
00:30:12.958 --> 00:30:14.267
Do you know each other?

445
00:30:14.291 --> 00:30:16.083
Never seen him before. sir.

446
00:30:17.625 --> 00:30:18.958
Leave him.

447
00:30:19.916 --> 00:30:21.267
Did you do it?

448
00:30:21.291 --> 00:30:22.642
Of course not.

449
00:30:22.666 --> 00:30:25.583
What is his theory. that I
broke in through the window?

450
00:30:26.083 --> 00:30:27.166
I believe so.

451
00:30:27.625 --> 00:30:29.851
Why would I do that if I had a key?

452
00:30:29.875 --> 00:30:32.892
Mycroft. what the bloody hell is
going on? This brother of yours.

453
00:30:32.916 --> 00:30:35.226
- Yes sir.
- One minute he's a redeemed felon.

454
00:30:35.250 --> 00:30:37.476
then he's servant.
then he's a felon again.

455
00:30:37.500 --> 00:30:40.017
and now apparently he's a linguist.

456
00:30:40.041 --> 00:30:42.851
Again. it's not a very interesting story. sir.

457
00:30:42.875 --> 00:30:45.476
The thief was here at
six minutes past 10:00.

458
00:30:45.500 --> 00:30:46.726
How can you possibly know that?

459
00:30:46.750 --> 00:30:50.500
Because when he climbed down
from the window. he knocked this off.

460
00:30:51.708 --> 00:30:53.309
The clue is in the clock.

461
00:30:53.333 --> 00:30:55.226
And you didn't notice this. constable?

462
00:30:55.250 --> 00:30:57.059
I can help you find your father's scrolls.

463
00:30:57.083 --> 00:30:59.809
There's a very good reason why
you can help find them. You stole them.

464
00:30:59.833 --> 00:31:01.851
This is not proper procedure.

465
00:31:01.875 --> 00:31:05.351
Sir. I represent the law.
I will do the investigation.

466
00:31:05.375 --> 00:31:07.434
And they're my father's scrolls.

467
00:31:07.458 --> 00:31:10.809
Need I remind you. sir. how
much of your trade with China

468
00:31:10.833 --> 00:31:12.458
relies on my father's goodwill.

469
00:31:13.250 --> 00:31:15.601
We are running late for your
appointment with the Dean. sir.

470
00:31:15.625 --> 00:31:16.726
Indeed.

471
00:31:16.750 --> 00:31:19.142
Perhaps we should give
the Princess a chance

472
00:31:19.166 --> 00:31:21.351
to conduct this
investigation as she sees fit.

473
00:31:21.375 --> 00:31:23.291
- I must protest.
- Really? Must you?

474
00:31:24.166 --> 00:31:26.375
Thank you. constable.
we'll take it from here.

475
00:31:28.000 --> 00:31:31.601
According to lestrade. the thief
scaled down the side of the building

476
00:31:31.625 --> 00:31:32.684
and into a boat.

477
00:31:32.708 --> 00:31:34.851
Lestrade told me there's
a river in the woods

478
00:31:34.875 --> 00:31:37.142
where the thief rowed
from candlin college.

479
00:31:37.166 --> 00:31:40.017
The thief rowed out from candlin college.
then got out here with the scrolls.

480
00:31:40.041 --> 00:31:41.851
- And then?
- Disappeared.

481
00:31:41.875 --> 00:31:42.934
Disappeared?

482
00:31:42.958 --> 00:31:44.642
We have no idea where they went. sir.

483
00:31:44.666 --> 00:31:45.750
Footprints?

484
00:31:46.333 --> 00:31:49.517
Only one set of tracks. only one thief.

485
00:31:49.541 --> 00:31:50.708
Headed off this way.

486
00:31:52.625 --> 00:31:53.625
Footprints end here.

487
00:31:55.166 --> 00:31:56.809
Thief got into a carriage.

488
00:31:56.833 --> 00:31:57.833
Aye. aye.

489
00:31:58.875 --> 00:32:01.517
Looks like one of them
wheels was a little drunk.

490
00:32:01.541 --> 00:32:04.309
And a drunk wheel
would need to sober up.

491
00:32:04.333 --> 00:32:06.833
Hello. A coaching inn?

492
00:32:07.375 --> 00:32:09.125
Where one might get a wheel fixed.

493
00:32:09.750 --> 00:32:12.541
I wanted to ask. Were
you trying to impress me?

494
00:32:14.458 --> 00:32:15.642
Impress you?

495
00:32:15.666 --> 00:32:16.976
At the maths lecture.

496
00:32:17.000 --> 00:32:18.392
Y.

497
00:32:18.416 --> 00:32:21.434
- When you corrected professor Thompson.
- Y.

498
00:32:21.458 --> 00:32:24.583
The professor's calculations
were incorrect. That was all.

499
00:32:25.083 --> 00:32:26.142
Disappointing.

500
00:32:26.166 --> 00:32:28.559
Well. frankly. I don't
know what you see in him.

501
00:32:28.583 --> 00:32:33.184
I mean. yes. he is some way handsome
in a sort of obvious. clumsy kind of way.

502
00:32:33.208 --> 00:32:36.476
but if you were ever looking
for something a bit more niche.

503
00:32:36.500 --> 00:32:38.726
a bit more bespoke.
more mysterious. well...

504
00:32:38.750 --> 00:32:40.892
where might the Princess
find a man like that?

505
00:32:40.916 --> 00:32:43.226
As stimulating as this is. chaps.

506
00:32:43.250 --> 00:32:45.017
I need to return to my carriage.

507
00:32:45.041 --> 00:32:46.976
- Why?
- The gala opening.

508
00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:50.375
Hodge's new science building.
I promised him I would be there.

509
00:32:51.041 --> 00:32:52.708
Thank you. For your help.

510
00:32:55.416 --> 00:32:56.666
Your royal highness.

511
00:32:57.166 --> 00:33:02.017
A welcomed oasis in the parched
deserts of this rural wasteland.

512
00:33:07.625 --> 00:33:09.309
What can I do for you. gentlemen?

513
00:33:09.333 --> 00:33:11.059
Two whiskeys. my good lady.

514
00:33:11.083 --> 00:33:12.934
and whatever you'd like for your fine self.

515
00:33:12.958 --> 00:33:13.958
Thank you.

516
00:33:14.458 --> 00:33:17.226
Aye now. I'm getting this.
Your money's no good here.

517
00:33:17.250 --> 00:33:19.958
I'll get the drinks. you get the tip.

518
00:33:21.875 --> 00:33:24.684
"And out of his pocket. he
pulled the sovereigns bright…"

519
00:33:24.708 --> 00:33:29.125
"…and the landlady's eyes
opened wide with delight."

520
00:33:29.625 --> 00:33:33.059
Excuse me. Our carriage
is in need of a bit of repair.

521
00:33:33.083 --> 00:33:35.708
Is the wheelwright around. and
might we have a word with him?

522
00:33:36.208 --> 00:33:39.041
He's down at the village.
but he'll be back shortly.

523
00:33:40.541 --> 00:33:41.541
We can wait.

524
00:33:53.875 --> 00:33:56.309
Are we playing the
game of getting another.

525
00:33:56.333 --> 00:33:58.351
or are we playing follow the Fiddler?

526
00:33:58.375 --> 00:34:01.541
Well… …I'll take care of the
former if you take care of the latter.

527
00:34:02.333 --> 00:34:03.392
It is your round.

528
00:34:39.500 --> 00:34:40.934
Hey. Sherlock!

529
00:34:48.125 --> 00:34:52.166
He has the scrolls. He's got the scrolls.

530
00:35:05.416 --> 00:35:08.184
When are you going to stop
blocking people's fists with your nose?

531
00:35:08.208 --> 00:35:10.226
- It wasn't his fists. It was his forehead.
- Yes.

532
00:35:10.250 --> 00:35:12.767
When you're engaged in combat.
it actually helps to throw a punch

533
00:35:12.791 --> 00:35:13.916
from time to time.

534
00:35:20.708 --> 00:35:22.208
He pulled his punch.

535
00:35:31.666 --> 00:35:32.750
What is this place?

536
00:35:33.458 --> 00:35:35.708
You're here too.

537
00:35:36.500 --> 00:35:38.583
Welcome to my over active imagination.

538
00:35:39.416 --> 00:35:40.726
Why pull your punch?

539
00:35:40.750 --> 00:35:42.476
- He can hear you?
- Yes.

540
00:35:42.500 --> 00:35:44.125
- But he can't answer you?
- No.

541
00:35:44.875 --> 00:35:46.601
Those are the rules I didn't make them.

542
00:35:46.625 --> 00:35:48.351
- Now he's paused.
- Yes.

543
00:35:48.375 --> 00:35:50.791
Waiting for something.
What's he waiting for?

544
00:35:52.333 --> 00:35:53.958
He's waiting for me to come out.

545
00:35:55.916 --> 00:35:57.000
Hey. Sherlock!

546
00:35:59.041 --> 00:36:01.476
Lovely tackle.

547
00:36:01.500 --> 00:36:03.041
Why wait for you to come out?

548
00:36:06.958 --> 00:36:08.166
Why don't you ask him?

549
00:36:30.166 --> 00:36:31.958
You can put them canons down.

550
00:36:35.750 --> 00:36:39.250
Now. I don't know if whether
I should split your Swede

551
00:36:40.666 --> 00:36:42.000
or smash your caps?

552
00:36:43.083 --> 00:36:44.267
What do you reckon?

553
00:36:44.291 --> 00:36:46.791
Decisions. decisions.

554
00:36:48.416 --> 00:36:51.059
- Why don't you ask my chum?
- I think the Swede.

555
00:36:58.458 --> 00:37:02.083
That's interesting. Not
exactly brimming with scrolls.

556
00:37:04.666 --> 00:37:06.017
I smell a rat?

557
00:37:06.041 --> 00:37:08.559
What if he pulled his punch
because he wanted to lure us away?

558
00:37:08.583 --> 00:37:10.583
Well. then someone
doesn't want us in Oxford.

559
00:37:11.916 --> 00:37:13.333
It's not even the same tube.

560
00:37:16.750 --> 00:37:18.851
We've been gifted a couple of paw prints.

561
00:37:18.875 --> 00:37:22.416
How did you develop these
skills of penetrating deduction?

562
00:37:24.333 --> 00:37:27.267
There are hand prints on
either side of the window.

563
00:37:27.291 --> 00:37:28.976
So he couldn't have
been holding the scrolls.

564
00:37:29.000 --> 00:37:31.166
What happens if he has
them strapped to his back?

565
00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:34.142
No. that's too big a
cork for too small a bottle.

566
00:37:34.166 --> 00:37:36.000
So he hands them to an accomplice?

567
00:37:37.125 --> 00:37:41.059
Only one set of tracks. Only one thief.

568
00:37:41.083 --> 00:37:44.101
So he leaves them on the inside
ledge and he reaches back for them?

569
00:37:44.125 --> 00:37:45.767
Wouldn't put him down as a gymnast.

570
00:37:45.791 --> 00:37:48.875
What if they never left?

571
00:37:49.916 --> 00:37:52.083
What if the scrolls are still in the library?

572
00:37:53.333 --> 00:37:55.291
- That's one hypothesis.
- You have a better one?

573
00:37:55.875 --> 00:37:57.809
In the unlikely event that you are right…

574
00:37:57.833 --> 00:38:00.767
- Why make it look like there was a theft…
- …if there was no theft?

575
00:38:00.791 --> 00:38:01.791
That's the question.

576
00:38:03.666 --> 00:38:04.958
You ever use one of these?

577
00:38:05.458 --> 00:38:06.559
Indeed I have.

578
00:38:06.583 --> 00:38:08.934
The devil do they think they're doing?

579
00:38:10.125 --> 00:38:11.333
Get back here!

580
00:38:12.083 --> 00:38:16.684
There is a special place in
hell for penny farthing thieves!

581
00:38:16.708 --> 00:38:19.083
We're pedalling there as fast as we can.

582
00:38:21.916 --> 00:38:23.583
Hold on. this doesn't make sense.

583
00:38:25.083 --> 00:38:27.517
The lead is cracked. Stress fracture.

584
00:38:27.541 --> 00:38:30.976
- It's not been pushed from the outside in…
- it's been pushed from the inside out.

585
00:38:31.000 --> 00:38:34.625
And then back in again. to make it look
like it was pushed in from the outside.

586
00:38:36.208 --> 00:38:37.666
Well. this wasn't a break in.

587
00:38:38.291 --> 00:38:40.375
but it's been made to
look like it was a break in.

588
00:38:45.750 --> 00:38:48.500
- Is that where my statue's going to go?
- I believe so. sir.

589
00:38:49.000 --> 00:38:53.333
I feel it needs to be… …

590
00:38:53.833 --> 00:38:56.601
- Bigger?
- Bigger. mycroft. Yes. bigger.

591
00:38:56.625 --> 00:39:01.416
Just higher than all those kings
and queens and saints and whatnot.

592
00:39:02.500 --> 00:39:07.166
Princess. so generous of you to
find time for my humble little shindig.

593
00:39:07.916 --> 00:39:09.125
The pleasure is mine.

594
00:39:10.333 --> 00:39:12.476
So the scrolls should
be in here somewhere.

595
00:39:12.500 --> 00:39:14.333
There's a thousand places to hide them.

596
00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:16.934
Yes. that does provide a challenge.

597
00:39:26.666 --> 00:39:27.958
Well. maybe you were wrong.

598
00:39:28.625 --> 00:39:29.892
- I was wrong?
- Yes.

599
00:39:29.916 --> 00:39:31.976
About the scrolls being
here. that was all you.

600
00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:33.892
Remind me. what was your theory?

601
00:39:33.916 --> 00:39:36.059
You can't rush genius.

602
00:39:36.083 --> 00:39:39.559
No. you take your time. It's not
you who's going back to prison.

603
00:39:39.583 --> 00:39:41.601
Well. maybe if you were a
more accomplished pickpocket.

604
00:39:41.625 --> 00:39:44.708
then you wouldn't be going
there in the first place. Would you?

605
00:39:49.416 --> 00:39:51.267
We've been looking for a something.

606
00:39:51.291 --> 00:39:54.416
When we should've been
looking for a someone. Walker.

607
00:39:55.625 --> 00:39:57.458
- Who?
- Walker the Porter.

608
00:39:58.541 --> 00:40:00.125
The Porter who tidies the room.

609
00:40:01.041 --> 00:40:03.517
He suffers from chronic scrupulosity.

610
00:40:03.541 --> 00:40:04.851
Every night he walks around

611
00:40:04.875 --> 00:40:08.392
and makes sure everything in
here is in order. everything is straight.

612
00:40:08.416 --> 00:40:11.351
Not just straight. as an arrow straight.

613
00:40:11.375 --> 00:40:14.142
Cushion. He hasn't
been here since the crime.

614
00:40:14.166 --> 00:40:17.809
So. something or
someone is not straight.

615
00:40:17.833 --> 00:40:18.833
John donne.

616
00:40:21.875 --> 00:40:23.226
He's been to the pub.

617
00:40:23.250 --> 00:40:24.333
He's had a drink.

618
00:40:25.000 --> 00:40:27.017
- A drink or two.
- He could have another.

619
00:40:27.041 --> 00:40:30.500
He should go home… but
he doesn't know when to stop.

620
00:40:35.916 --> 00:40:37.041
That's beginner's luck.

621
00:40:39.083 --> 00:40:43.458
Our secret lies in confusing the enemy
so he cannot fathom our true intent.

622
00:40:44.041 --> 00:40:45.351
What if it was a diversion?

623
00:40:45.375 --> 00:40:47.601
The library is the busiest room in college.

624
00:40:47.625 --> 00:40:50.601
Even at night. porters check
on the place every 30 minutes.

625
00:40:50.625 --> 00:40:53.392
The thief makes it seem as
though the scrolls were stolen

626
00:40:53.416 --> 00:40:56.184
to ensure the library is
sealed off as a crime scene.

627
00:40:56.208 --> 00:41:00.851
He then squirrels himself away in here
and waits for all to be quiet and clear.

628
00:41:00.875 --> 00:41:03.142
He needs to be
undisturbed. He needs time.

629
00:41:03.166 --> 00:41:04.625
Time? Time for what?

630
00:41:10.625 --> 00:41:16.392
This is the case that held the
scrolls. Our whiskey has made its Mark.

631
00:41:16.416 --> 00:41:20.434
Now. before the scrolls were
stolen. this case sat atop a cabinet.

632
00:41:20.458 --> 00:41:25.351
The cabinet which is now missing.
Why was it taken and what was inside it?

633
00:41:25.375 --> 00:41:27.059
Let's focus on the how

634
00:41:27.083 --> 00:41:29.101
and that will give us
the what and the why.

635
00:41:29.125 --> 00:41:34.625
Now. how does a cabinet disappear
when the police are at the only door?

636
00:41:36.166 --> 00:41:40.142
Through the walls. In its
original incarnation 400 years ago.

637
00:41:40.166 --> 00:41:42.559
before this was a library.
what was this room?

638
00:41:42.583 --> 00:41:43.892
A medieval banqueting hall.

639
00:41:43.916 --> 00:41:46.142
So there would've been five corridors.

640
00:41:46.166 --> 00:41:48.434
- One for the Norman aristocracy.
- Two for the masses.

641
00:41:48.458 --> 00:41:50.934
And two for the servants
coming in and out from the kitchen.

642
00:41:50.958 --> 00:41:52.625
All bricked up and panel led over.

643
00:41:54.375 --> 00:41:58.125
Rat-a-ta-tat.

644
00:42:08.166 --> 00:42:09.166
Cat follows rat?

645
00:42:10.708 --> 00:42:11.750
Cat follows rat.

646
00:42:23.708 --> 00:42:25.250
Well. we've found our cabinet.

647
00:42:28.166 --> 00:42:32.166
Now we know how it got here.
shall we address the what?

648
00:42:32.833 --> 00:42:34.250
Door number one.

649
00:42:35.791 --> 00:42:39.666
we have some kind
of mechanical activator.

650
00:42:40.166 --> 00:42:41.226
Door number two…

651
00:42:45.625 --> 00:42:48.416
The mechanism. it's
activating. Door number three…

652
00:42:49.833 --> 00:42:51.184
A timing device.

653
00:42:51.208 --> 00:42:53.291
Door number four… hazard a guess?

654
00:42:58.000 --> 00:42:59.267
Dear.

655
00:42:59.291 --> 00:43:00.559
Well. now we know the what.

656
00:43:00.583 --> 00:43:01.726
So. what's the why?

657
00:43:04.291 --> 00:43:09.309
Nothing has such power to broaden
the mind as the ability to investigate.

658
00:43:09.333 --> 00:43:11.767
- To investigate is to wonder.
- Hodge's gala.

659
00:43:11.791 --> 00:43:13.500
Do you know how to
defuse one of these?

660
00:43:14.333 --> 00:43:15.851
No. Do you?

661
00:43:15.875 --> 00:43:16.875
Can we move it?

662
00:43:18.125 --> 00:43:19.434
- I wouldn't.
- Solution?

663
00:43:19.458 --> 00:43:21.517
Well. we've only got 90
seconds according to that clock.

664
00:43:21.541 --> 00:43:24.392
This building will be
a cathedral to science.

665
00:43:24.416 --> 00:43:26.416
The stone and mortar that surround us…

666
00:43:27.125 --> 00:43:29.809
…a cathedral to science.

667
00:43:29.833 --> 00:43:33.267
I must now make mention
of our brilliant mathematician.

668
00:43:33.291 --> 00:43:36.226
professor Charles Thompson
for his invaluable contribution.

669
00:43:36.250 --> 00:43:38.142
Lords…

670
00:43:38.166 --> 00:43:40.726
…ladies and gentlemen. I
invite you to charge your glasses.

671
00:43:52.666 --> 00:43:54.934
Holmes. what the devil are
you doing in my chimney?

672
00:43:54.958 --> 00:43:57.434
Sorry to bother you. sir.
A rather pressing issue.

673
00:43:57.458 --> 00:43:59.767
- I hope it is for your sake. What is it?
- A bomb.

674
00:43:59.791 --> 00:44:02.351
- What do you mean a bomb?
- A bomb is an incendiary device...

675
00:44:02.375 --> 00:44:04.642
I know what a bloody bomb is. Holmes.

676
00:44:04.666 --> 00:44:07.726
what does that got to do with interrupting
my speech and destroying my chimney?

677
00:44:07.750 --> 00:44:10.892
Proximity. sir. It's likely to
go off in the next 30 seconds.

678
00:44:10.916 --> 00:44:12.767
killing anyone within the blast radius.

679
00:44:12.791 --> 00:44:15.559
which I would assume is likely to
be pretty much this whole room. sir.

680
00:44:15.583 --> 00:44:17.916
I see. Well. that does
seem to be a sound reason.

681
00:44:18.583 --> 00:44:22.267
For god's sake. would you stop
being so English? There's a bomb!

682
00:44:22.291 --> 00:44:24.708
A bomb!

683
00:44:58.666 --> 00:45:00.767
Whoever's behind this.
I'm going to string them up.

684
00:45:00.791 --> 00:45:02.476
cut them down while they're still alive.

685
00:45:02.500 --> 00:45:04.833
disembowel them and burn
their entrails before their eyes.

686
00:45:05.750 --> 00:45:07.041
Entrails. Very good. sir.

687
00:45:36.208 --> 00:45:39.517
So what exactly are we celebrating?
We haven't solved anything.

688
00:45:39.541 --> 00:45:41.559
We don't know who
planted the bomb. Or why.

689
00:45:43.833 --> 00:45:45.059
And that is not our concern.

690
00:45:45.083 --> 00:45:46.434
That's not our concern?

691
00:45:46.458 --> 00:45:48.851
We set out to find the
scrolls. We found them.

692
00:45:48.875 --> 00:45:51.666
I'm not losing my scholarship
and you're not going to prison.

693
00:45:52.916 --> 00:45:54.916
So I think that's worth raising a glass to.

694
00:46:02.916 --> 00:46:04.125
Why aren't you drinking?

695
00:46:04.916 --> 00:46:05.916
Not thirsty.

696
00:46:09.291 --> 00:46:10.291
Come in.

697
00:46:12.208 --> 00:46:14.351
Another survivor?

698
00:46:14.375 --> 00:46:18.916
Yes. but I can't pretend
I'm not shaken. Please sit.

699
00:46:22.791 --> 00:46:24.041
Can I have one of those?

700
00:46:25.208 --> 00:46:26.642
Yes. of course.

701
00:46:26.666 --> 00:46:28.166
Please come in. Close the door.

702
00:46:37.708 --> 00:46:39.208
Well. at least someone's thirsty.

703
00:46:39.875 --> 00:46:44.375
I wanted to thank you. Sherlock.
for finding my father's scrolls.

704
00:46:45.500 --> 00:46:49.500
Well. don't mind me. I'm
just an ashkenazi side dish.

705
00:46:52.125 --> 00:46:54.166
Besides. I have a previous arrangement.

706
00:46:55.250 --> 00:46:56.309
Do you?

707
00:46:56.333 --> 00:46:58.684
You're much more than
chopped liver my friend.

708
00:46:58.708 --> 00:47:00.476
you must stay. you're the main course.

709
00:47:00.500 --> 00:47:01.708
No. No. no. no. no.

710
00:47:02.208 --> 00:47:07.184
So… Romeo. Juliet.
Goodnight. goodnight.

711
00:47:07.208 --> 00:47:10.958
Parting is such sweet sorrow
that I should say goodnight…

712
00:47:13.541 --> 00:47:15.226
'Cause I'm off to the pub.

713
00:47:21.958 --> 00:47:24.601
Now. how should I reward you?

714
00:47:24.625 --> 00:47:26.916
No. that's not necessary.

715
00:47:27.583 --> 00:47:29.166
At least let me top you up.

716
00:47:33.708 --> 00:47:34.708
Thank you.

717
00:47:36.875 --> 00:47:40.851
Your companion. James
moriarty. is quite brilliant.

718
00:47:40.875 --> 00:47:43.267
But not as brilliant as you.

719
00:47:49.708 --> 00:47:51.958
Here's to your extraordinary future.

720
00:48:01.583 --> 00:48:02.750
You missed a bit.

721
00:48:08.916 --> 00:48:11.500
Why don't you sit down over
there and I'll clean you up?

722
00:48:14.416 --> 00:48:17.434
I'm not quite sure this is all… I insist.

723
00:48:30.583 --> 00:48:33.583
Tick… tock.

724
00:48:34.166 --> 00:48:36.000
Come play with me. Sherlock.

725
00:48:37.083 --> 00:48:38.309
Play with her.

726
00:48:38.333 --> 00:48:41.375
Sherlock. why don't you
play with your sister? Go on.

727
00:48:42.375 --> 00:48:43.767
Get up you idiot.

728
00:48:46.291 --> 00:48:47.666
Play with her.

729
00:48:50.291 --> 00:48:51.291
Bea?

730
00:48:52.041 --> 00:48:54.059
- Where is she?
- Cordelia?

731
00:48:54.083 --> 00:48:56.017
- Beatrice!
- Beatrice!

732
00:48:56.041 --> 00:48:58.208
Bea! Beatrice!

733
00:49:04.750 --> 00:49:06.309
My god!

734
00:49:06.333 --> 00:49:07.476
Your fault.

735
00:49:07.500 --> 00:49:09.208
Open up!

736
00:49:14.708 --> 00:49:16.791
Police! Open up!

737
00:49:18.166 --> 00:49:20.458
That's him. Get him on his feet. lads.

738
00:49:24.416 --> 00:49:25.791
Sherlock Holmes.

739
00:49:27.625 --> 00:49:30.458
I'm arresting you for the murder
of professor Charles Thompson.

740
00:49:31.625 --> 00:49:32.750
Take him away.

740
00:49:33.305 --> 00:50:33.316
